-parts":[[2022,8,2]],"date-time":"2022-08-02T20:45:29Z","timestamp":1659473129148},"reference-count":0,"publisher":"Oxford University Press","content-domain":{"domain":[],"crossmark-restriction":false},"published-print":{"date-parts":[[2017,5,18]]},"abstract":"<p>This chapter defends a <italic>causalist<\/italic> position on the explanation of intentional human actions. It defends the thesis that one necessary condition for an adequate explanation of such an action is that the explanation cite a cause of the action. Various options for a required causal condition are identified, including causation by reasons, by beliefs, desires, or intentions, by neural realizers of mental states of these kinds, or by facts about something the agents believed, desired, or intended. Leading anticausalist proposals are rebutted. A major problem highlighted for these proposals features cases in which an agent who has two or more reasons for performing a certain action performs it for only one of those reasons.<\/p>","DOI":"10.1093\/acprof:oso\/9780190659974.003.0003","type":"book","created":{"date-parts":[[2017,5,17]],"date-time":"2017-05-17T14:46:18Z","timestamp":1495032378000},"source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":0,"title":["Actions, Explanations, and Causes"],"prefix":"10.1093","author":[{"given":"Alfred R.","family":"Mele","sequence":"first","affiliation":[]}],"member":"286","container-title":["Oxford Scholarship Online"],"original-title":["Actions, Explanations, and Causes"],"deposited":{"date-parts":[[2022,8,2]],"date-time":"2022-08-02T20:19:10Z","timestamp":1659471550000},"score":25.571383,"resource":{"primary":{"URL":"https:\/\/academic.oup.com\/book\/2489\/chapter\/142773083"}},"issued":{"date-parts":[[2017,5,18]]},"references-count":0,"URL":"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/acprof:oso\/9780190659974.003.0003","published":{"date-parts":[[2017,5,18]]}},{"indexed":{"date-parts":[[2024,5,9]],"date-time":"2024-05-09T23:15:45Z","timestamp":1715296545458},"reference-count":0,"publisher":"Manchester University Press","isbn-type":[{"value":"9780719088919","type":"print"},{"value":"9781526138729","type":"electronic"}],"content-domain":{"domain":[],"crossmark-restriction":false},"published-print":{"date-parts":[[2018,11,1]]},"abstract":"<p>The chapter explores how corruption can be explained or accounted for. It argues that there are two very broad questions facing scholars who have sought to explain corruption: 1) Under what conditions will individuals become caught up in it either as corruptors or the corrupted? 2) What explains why levels of corruption appear to be higher in some contexts than in others? The two questions, though related, are different. Thus, one of the suggestions one might make to explain why corruption seems more widespread among Nigerian than among UK civil servants, say, is that the former are paid much less than the latter. But though lower salaries might throw light on why there is more corruption among Nigerian than among British civil servants generally, it will not help us to understand why some Nigerian civil servants, assuming their salaries are uniformly low, behave corruptly while others remain honest. The chapter is therefore divided into two sections corresponding to the questions identified above followed by a section drawing some conclusions for the issue to be considered in the following chapter: the mechanisms and dynamics of corruption.<\/p>","DOI":"10.7228\/manchester\/9780719088919.003.0003","type":"book-chapter","created":{"date-parts":[[2019,1,25]],"date-time":"2019-01-25T00:45:31Z","timestamp":1548377131000},"page":"43-63","source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":0,"title":["The causes and explanations of political corruption"],"prefix":"10.7228","author":[{"given":"James L.","family":"Newell","sequence":"first","affiliation":[]}],"member":"4230","published-online":{"date-parts":[[2019,1,24]]},"container-title":["Corruption in contemporary politics"],"original-title":["The causes and explanations of political corruption"],"language":"en","deposited":{"date-parts":[[2022,7,28]],"date-time":"2022-07-28T16:03:37Z","timestamp":1659024217000},"score":23.671436,"resource":{"primary":{"URL":"https:\/\/academic.oup.com\/manchester-scholarship-online\/book\/23941\/chapter\/185280176"}},"issued":{"date-parts":[[2018,11,1]]},"ISBN":["9780719088919","9781526138729"],"references-count":0,"URL":"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.7228\/manchester\/9780719088919.003.0003","published":{"date-parts":[[2018,11,1]]}},{"indexed":{"date-parts":[[2026,1,29]],"date-time":"2026-01-29T12:58:16Z","timestamp":1769691496710,"version":"3.49.0"},"reference-count":0,"publisher":"Oxford University Press","content-domain":{"domain":[],"crossmark-restriction":false},"published-print":{"date-parts":[[2018,6,21]]},"abstract":"<p>In the spirit of explanatory pluralism, this chapter argues that causal and non-causal explanations of a phenomenon are compatible, each being useful for bringing out different sorts of insights. First the chapter reviews the author\u2019s model-based account of scientific explanation, which can accommodate causal and non-causal explanations alike. Then it distills from the literature an important core conception of non-causal explanation. This non-causal form of model-based explanation is illustrated using the example of how Earth scientists in a subfield known as aeolian geomorphology are explaining the formation of regularly-spaced sand ripples. The chapter concludes that even when it comes to everyday \u201cmedium-sized dry goods\u201d such as sand ripples, where there is a complete causal story to be told, one can find examples of non-causal scientific explanations.<\/p>","DOI":"10.1093\/oso\/9780198777946.003.0008","type":"edited-book","created":{"date-parts":[[2018,6,21]],"date-time":"2018-06-21T08:38:05Z","timestamp":1529570285000},"source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":8,"title":["Searching for Non-Causal Explanations in a Sea of Causes"],"prefix":"10.1093","auth